    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Warn Africa On Diamond Trade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kenneth W Witwer letter says Pres Clinton should send not troops but warnings to Africans who finance killing with diamond money(S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''G.I.'s to Be Sent to Train Africans for Sierra Leone'' (front page, Aug. 9):</p>
        <p>The Revolutionary United Front war machine in Sierra Leone runs on diamond money. Faced with a United Nations embargo and De Beers's  tough new buying policy, the killers simply channel their gems through Liberia. Liberia's diamond exports have shown a sharp, telltale rise, and even the normally sanction-shy European Union has slapped penalties, at Britain's behest, on Liberia.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''G.I.'s to Be Sent to Train Africans for Sierra Leone'' (front page, Aug. 9):</p>
        <p>The Revolutionary United Front war machine in Sierra Leone runs on diamond money. Faced with a United Nations embargo and De Beers's  tough new buying policy, the killers simply channel their gems through Liberia. Liberia's diamond exports have shown a sharp, telltale rise, and even the normally sanction-shy European Union has slapped penalties, at Britain's behest, on Liberia.</p>
        <p>But the United States refuses to help out, even to admonish. Why? Some would point to the special envoy to Africa, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has voiced praise for Foday Sankoh, the R.U.F.'s leader, and who is a longtime friend of Liberia's president, Charles Taylor.</p>
        <p>President Clinton should not send G.I.'s to Africa. He should send Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright to Freetown with a friendly warning.  KENNETH W. WITWER  Lancaster, Pa., Aug. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
